# Some of Jinhua's Code
plot_cmethod = function(x_dat, y_dat, title, x_label, y_label, colors, shapes, 
                        save_name = NA, 
                        legend_names = c("Pitch type: FC","Pitch type: FF",x_label,y_label)) {
    plot(x_dat,y_dat,main = title, xlab = "First PC", ylab = "Second PC", col=colors, pch=shapes)
    legend("bottomleft", legend_names,
           pch=c(20,20,2,1), col = c(1,2,1,1),cex = 0.75)
    if(!is.na(save_name)) {
        dev.copy(png, save_name)
        dev.off()
    }
}

get_ward_cluster = function(dat_scaled, cut_h = 2) {
    d = dist(dat_scaled, "euclidean", p = 2)   # euclidean distance matrix
    w = hclust(d, method = "ward.D")   
    return(cutree(w, h = cut_h))
}

Load Data¶

The pitchRx library allows one to easily obtain Major League Baseball's (heretofore MLB) Gameday data, which includes a dataset known as PITCHf/x. PITCHf/x contains records data on every pitch throw in the MLB and with this data the MLB is able to classify the types of pitches for each player.

Dataset Used:¶

The pitchRx library comes with a dataset (called "pitches") of all pitches classified as four-seam fastballs (FF) and cut fastballs (FC) thrown by Mariano Rivera and Phil Hughes in the 2011 regular season. Additionally, we used the pitchRx library to obtain all of the pitches classified as FF or FC by Mariano Rivera and Phil Hughes in the 2010 regular season.

K-means Clustering¶

For our first analysis, we will run a K-means test on the data from 2011 with 2 clusters for each of our two pitchers. The K-means test tries to minimize the distance between the Euclidean distance between a cluster mean and each point. The K-means algorithm initially randomly assigns K cluster prototypes. Then each point is assigned to a cluster after which the cluster prototypes are reassigned to the centroid of the assigned cluster masses. This process is repeated n number of times or until the prototypes remain stationary.

Importantly, the random nature of the initial assignment of the prototypes means that cluster labels may not hold during subsequent runs. Thus the clustering assignments of "1" and "2" do not necessarily equal "FF" or "FC", although classifying our clusters as a certain pitch type will hopefully be trivial if we obtain results similar to MLB. We used both the scaled and unscaled data to determine if one was more appropriate for this and our other tests.

rivera.2011.kmeans = rivera.2011.kmeans.pSC
hughes.2011.kmeans = hughes.2011.kmeans.pSC

Summary¶

These results show that the cluster formation using the scaled data is more closely related to the clustering and subsequent classification used by Major League Baseball (MLB). This makes sense as data with features of different measurements is affected by factor scaling. Thus scaling makes analyses with things such as PCA ppossible. For the remainder of this analysis, we have only used the scaled data.

Support Vector Machine Classification¶

Support Vector Machines (SVMs for short) are a supervised machine learning method for classifying data using a training set and a testing set. The supervised learning methods take the training dataset and builds a model to classify the data points in such a way that minimizes a given cost function. The models are generally built with different mathematical similarity functions called kernels that project the data linearly or non-linearly so that it can be more easily divided with a hyperplane / hypershape to classify the projected data. The R package, e1071, comes with several kernels and parameters for those kernels. We explored the different kernels, but ended up only using one in our analysis. We chose a kernel commonly used in SVM called the Radial Basis Function kernel, which is a similarity function dependent on the squared Euclidean distance between two points and a free factor known as gamma.

SVM, supervised learning, and classification are different than clustering. However our application of clustering led to the ability to trivially classify our results, because we were comparing our clustering results to MLB's classification. We thought it would be interesting to add a classification method to our analysis to see how it stacks up against our clusters and MLB's classifications.

Our Method¶

1) Train 2 SVM models with data from 2010, one for each pitcher
2) Use 2010 data to tune model (optional) 3) Use these models to classify the pitches with the 2011 data
4) Analyze results

In [8]:
# SVM
# http://rischanlab.github.io/SVM.html
print("Support Vector Machines")
print("Classify 2011 Pitches w/2010 Training Data")

print("Mariano Rivera")
#radial kernel
#rivera.2010.svm_tune = tune(svm, train.x=rivera.2010.pSC, train.y=as.factor(rivera.2010$pitch_type), 
#                            kernel="radial", ranges=list(cost=10^(-1:2), gamma=c(1/dim(rivera.2010.pSC)[2],.5,1,2)))
#print(rivera.2010.svm_tune)
rivera.2010.svm_model = svm(rivera.2010.pSC, as.factor(rivera.2010$pitch_type),
                           kernel="radial",gamma=1/dim(rivera.2010.pSC)[2], cost=1)


rivera.2011.svm = predict(rivera.2010.svm_model, rivera.2011.pSC)
table(rivera.2011$pitch_type, rivera.2011.svm)
plot_cmethod(rivera.2011.pca$x[,"PC1"], rivera.2011.pca$x[,"PC2"], "Mariano Rivera's_SVM Method", 
             "SVM FF", "SVM FC", as.factor(rivera.2011$pitch_type), as.numeric(as.factor(rivera.2011.svm)))


print("Phil Hughes")
#hughes.2010.svm_tune = tune(svm, train.x=hughes.2010.pSC, train.y=as.factor(hughes.2010$pitch_type), 
#                            kernel="radial", ranges=list(cost=10^(-1:2), gamma=c(1/dim(hughes.2010.pSC)[2],.5,1,2)))
#print(hughes_svm_tune)
hughes.2010.svm_model = svm(hughes.2010.pSC, as.factor(hughes.2010$pitch_type),
                            kernel="radial",gamma=1/dim(hughes.2010.pSC)[2], cost=1)

hughes.2011.svm = predict(hughes.2010.svm_model, hughes.2011.pSC)
table(hughes.2011$pitch_type, hughes.2011.svm)
plot_cmethod(hughes.2011.pca$x[,"PC1"], hughes.2011.pca$x[,"PC2"], "Phil Hughes's_SVM Method", 
             "SVM FF", "SVM FC", as.factor(hughes.2011$pitch_type), as.numeric(as.factor(hughes.2011.svm)))
